{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Statutory Regulations",
      "simpleDefinition": "Laws passed by Parliament that are mandatory and must be followed; failure to comply is a criminal offense.",
      "anchor": "The law of the land.",
      "misconception": "Thinking these are optional guidelines rather than legal requirements that can lead to prosecution."
    },
    {
      "term": "Non-statutory Regulations",
      "simpleDefinition": "Professional standards and codes of practice that provide guidance on how to meet legal requirements.",
      "anchor": "The industry's rulebook.",
      "misconception": "Believing that because they aren't laws, they can be ignored without any legal or professional consequence."
    },
    {
      "term": "HASAWA (Health and Safety at Work Act)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The primary piece of UK legislation covering occupational health and safety.",
      "anchor": "The umbrella act.",
      "misconception": "Thinking it only applies to employers and not to the individual employees or contractors."
    },
    {
      "term": "EAWR (Electricity at Work Regulations)",
      "simpleDefinition": "Statutory regulations specifically focused on preventing death or injury from electricity in the workplace.",
      "anchor": "The electrician's legal duty.",
      "misconception": "Confusing these legal requirements with the technical instructions found in BS 7671."
    },
    {
      "term": "BS 7671",
      "simpleDefinition": "The national standard for electrical installations in the UK, also known as the IET Wiring Regulations.",
      "anchor": "The Big Blue Book.",
      "misconception": "Mistakenly identifying BS 7671 as a statutory law when it is actually a non-statutory standard."
    },
    {
      "term": "On-Site Guide",
      "simpleDefinition": "A non-statutory publication that simplifies the requirements of BS 7671 for common installation types.",
      "anchor": "The practical toolkit.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the On-Site Guide contains every rule needed for complex industrial installations."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Statutory means it is the law.",
    "Non-statutory is the guidance to meet the law.",
    "BS 7671 is the industry standard, not the law.",
    "EAWR is the specific law for electrical safety."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Distinguish between a 'Regulation' that is law and a 'Regulation' that is a standard.",
    "Identify that BS 7671 is non-statutory.",
    "Recognize that HASAWA applies to everyone on site, not just the boss."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "203-1a-teach-check-1",
      "title": "Introduction to Industry Frameworks",
      "objective": "Explanation A",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In the electrical industry, we operate within a strict framework of rules to ensure safety and consistency. This framework is divided into two distinct categories: Statutory and Non-statutory. Statutory regulations are the law of the land; they are mandatory requirements passed by Parliament. If you fail to follow these, you are committing a criminal offense which can lead to prosecution, heavy fines, or even imprisonment.",
        "Non-statutory regulations, on the other hand, are professional standards and codes of practice. While they are not laws themselves, they represent the industry's 'best practice.' Following these standards is the most common way to prove in a court of law that you have met your legal (statutory) obligations. You must treat both categories with equal importance to ensure your work is safe, legal, and professional."
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on the distinction between a legal requirement (law) and a professional standard (best practice)."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-1a-teach-check-2",
      "title": "The Legal Weight of Regulations",
      "objective": "Explanation B",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "To understand the difference between the two types of regulations, you must look at the consequences of ignoring them. Statutory regulations are legally binding. This means that the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) can issue improvement or prohibition notices if they find you are in breach of these laws. Because they are legislation, they apply to everyone, including employers, employees, and self-employed contractors.",
        "Non-statutory guidance, such as the IET Wiring Regulations (BS 7671), provides the technical detail on how to achieve the safety required by law. Although BS 7671 is not a law, it is often cited in court. If an accident occurs and you can prove you followed BS 7671, it acts as a powerful defense. However, if you ignored it and an accident happened, it becomes very difficult to prove you were working safely according to the law."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about which one is a 'law' and which one is a 'standard' used to meet that law."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-1a-teach-check-3",
      "title": "Core Statutory Regulations",
      "objective": "Teach the core idea: statutory regulations.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Statutory regulations are the mandatory laws you must follow. The primary 'umbrella' law is HASAWA, which stands for the Health and Safety at Work Act. This act sets out the general duties of everyone in the workplace. Underneath this umbrella sits the EAWR, or the Electricity at Work Regulations. This is the specific law that governs electrical safety and places a legal duty on you to prevent danger from electricity.",
        "Other essential statutory regulations include PUWER (Provision and Use of Work Equipment Regulations), which ensures your tools are safe, and COSHH (Control of Substances Hazardous to Health), which covers dangerous chemicals like resins or cleaning fluids. You also have the ESQCR (Electricity Safety, Quality and Continuity Regulations), which mainly concerns the supply of electricity to the public. All of these are 'Acts' or 'Regulations' that carry the full weight of the law."
      ],
      "hint": "Look for acronyms like HASAWA and EAWR, which represent the primary laws for safety and electricity."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-1a-teach-check-4",
      "title": "Non-statutory Guidance and Standards",
      "objective": "Teach the core idea: non-statutory regulations/guidance.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Non-statutory regulations are the technical 'how-to' guides of the industry. The most important document is BS 7671, also known as the IET Wiring Regulations. Even though it has 'Regulations' in the title, it is a British Standard (BS), not a law. It is the national standard for the design, selection, and installation of electrical equipment. It is often referred to as the 'Big Blue Book' (or whatever color the current edition is).",
        "Other examples of non-statutory guidance include the On-Site Guide, which is a simplified version of BS 7671 for common installation types, and various Guidance Notes that provide deeper technical detail on specific topics like testing or earthing. There are also Codes of Practice and the Unite Union Book. These documents are designed to help you do the job correctly and safely, ensuring your work meets the high standards expected in the UK."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember that BS 7671 is a standard (non-statutory), even though it uses the word 'Regulations' in its name."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-1a-teach-check-5",
      "title": "Identifying Statutory Requirements",
      "objective": "Teach the core idea: 203.LO1.AC1.1.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Identifying statutory regulations is a key skill for any electrician. You can usually identify them because they are issued by the government and often include the year they were passed into law. For example, the Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations and the Construction (Design and Management) Regulations, known as CDM, are statutory. These laws are non-negotiable and apply to all construction sites.",
        "Other examples include the PPE (Personal Protective Equipment) at Work Regulations, which mandate that your employer provides safety gear, and the Manual Handling Operations Regulations, which cover how to lift heavy items safely. Even the Environmental Act and the DDA (Disability Discrimination Act) are statutory requirements that can affect how we design and install electrical systems. If it is a piece of legislation that can lead to a criminal record if ignored, it is statutory."
      ],
      "hint": "Statutory regulations are laws passed by government, often covering broad safety, equipment, or environmental rules."
    }
  ]
}

